{
  "Community Ecology": "社区生态学",
  "This lesson covers the fundamental measures of center used to analyze and summarize data sets. You'll learn how to calculate and apply the mean, median, and mode, and understand when each is most appropriate.": "这个课程涵盖了分析和总结数据集的中心的基本测量方法。 您将学会如何计算和应用平均值、 中位数和模式, 并了解何时最合适 。",
  "What is a biological community?": "什么是生物群落?",
  "A biological community consists of all the populations of different species living and interacting in a particular area at the same time. Unlike a population (one species) or an ecosystem (biotic + abiotic), a community focuses specifically on the interacting species. Community ecology studies how these species interact through competition, predation, symbiosis, and other relationships.": "生物群落由同时在特定区域生活和互动的不同物种的所有种群组成,与种群(一个物种)或生态系统(生物+非生物)不同,一个群落具体侧重于互动物种,社区生态研究这些物种如何通过竞争、掠夺、共生和其他关系相互作用。",
  "What is species richness?": "什么是物种丰富?",
  "Species richness is simply the count of different species present in a community. A tropical rainforest with 500 tree species has higher species richness than a temperate forest with 50 tree species. Species richness is one component of species diversity but does not account for how evenly individuals are distributed among those species.": "物种丰富性只是社区中不同物种的数数。 热带雨林有500个树种,其物种丰富性高于温带森林,温带森林有50个树种。 物种丰富性是物种多样性的一个组成部分,但没有说明这些物种中个人分布的均匀性。",
  "What is a keystone species?": "什么是关键物种?",
  "A keystone species exerts an influence on its community that is disproportionately large relative to its abundance or biomass. Removing a keystone species causes dramatic changes in community structure. The classic example is the sea star Pisaster in Pacific tide pools — its removal allows mussels to dominate, reducing species diversity from 15+ species to just a few.": "一个关键物种对其社区施加的影响与其丰富量或生物量相比不成比例地大。消除一个关键物种导致群落结构的巨变。典型的例子就是太平洋潮汐池中的海星比萨斯特 — — 其去除使贝类占据主导地位,将物种多样性从15+物种减少到少数。",
  "What is a foundation species?": "什么是基础物种?",
  "A foundation species creates or significantly modifies the physical habitat, enabling many other species to exist in the community. Unlike keystone species (influence disproportionate to abundance), foundation species typically have high abundance and physically structure the environment. Examples include coral (building reef structure), kelp (creating underwater forests), and large trees (forming forest canopy).": "与关键物种不同(与丰度不相称的影响),基础物种通常丰度高,环境结构自然,例如珊瑚(建造珊瑚礁结构)、海藻(形成水下森林)和大树(形成森林树冠)等。",
  "What is an indicator species?": "什么是指标物种?",
  "An indicator species is one whose presence, absence, or health reflects specific environmental conditions in the community. Scientists monitor indicator species to assess ecosystem health. For example, amphibians are indicators of water quality (they absorb pollutants through their skin), and lichens indicate air quality.": "科学家监测指标物种以评估生态系统健康,例如,两栖动物是水质指标(它们通过皮肤吸收污染物),地环显示空气质量。",
  "What is the intermediate disturbance hypothesis?": "中间扰动假设是什么?",
  "The intermediate disturbance hypothesis proposes that species diversity is highest at moderate (intermediate) levels of disturbance. Too little disturbance allows competitive dominants to exclude other species; too much disturbance eliminates all but the hardiest colonizers. Moderate disturbance prevents any one species from dominating while not being so frequent that sensitive species cannot establish.": "中间扰动假设认为,物种多样性在中度(中度)扰动水平上是最高的。 太多的扰动使得竞争优势能够排除其他物种;太多的扰动除最强硬的殖民者外,还消除了所有物种。 中度扰动阻止了任何一个物种占据主导地位,而同时又不那么频繁,以致敏感物种无法建立。",
  "What is the difference between a dominant species and a keystone species?": "主要物种与关键物种之间有什么区别?",
  "A dominant species controls the community through its sheer abundance or biomass (e.g., sugar maples dominating a forest canopy). A keystone species has an effect disproportionate to its relatively low abundance (e.g., sea stars controlling mussel populations). Both influence community structure, but through different mechanisms — abundance vs. outsized ecological role.": "一种主要物种通过其丰富的或生物量(例如,占森林树冠的糖层图象)来控制社区,一种关键物种的影响与其相对低的丰度不相称(例如,控制着贝类种群的海星),两者都影响社区结构,但通过不同的机制——丰度与超大小的生态作用。",
  "What is bottom-up control in a community?": "社区内什么是自下而上的控制?",
  "Bottom-up control (also called resource-driven control) means community structure is determined by factors at the base of the food web — nutrient availability, sunlight, and producer abundance. More nutrients → more producers → more herbivores → more predators. Changes ripple upward through trophic levels from the bottom.": "自下而上的控制(也称为资源驱动的控制)意味着社区结构是由食物网基点的各种因素——营养供应、阳光和生产者丰量——决定的。更多的营养养分 更多的养分 更多的食草动物 更多的食肉动物 更多的食肉动物。 变化从底部的营养水平向上波及。",
  "What is top-down control in a community?": "一个社区的自上而下控制是什么?",
  "Top-down control (predator-driven control) means that predators at higher trophic levels regulate the abundance of organisms at lower levels. This can create a trophic cascade: removing a top predator causes herbivore populations to explode, which overgrazes producers. The Yellowstone wolf reintroduction is a classic example of restoring top-down control.": "自上而下的控制(食肉动物驱动的控制)意味着较高营养级的食肉动物在较低层次监管生物的丰量。 这可能造成一个营养级联:除去顶层食肉动物导致食草动物爆发,从而过度放牧生产者。黄石狼的重新引入是恢复自上而下的控制的典型例子。",
  "Outliers and Resistant Measures": "外围和抵抗措施",
  "This is a textbook example of the intermediate disturbance hypothesis. No fire (low disturbance) → competitive dominants exclude others. Annual fire (high disturbance) → only fire-resistant species survive. Fire every 3-5 years (moderate disturbance) → prevents competitive exclusion but is infrequent enough for fire-sensitive species to establish between burns, maximizing diversity.": "这是中度扰动假设的教科书例子。 没有火灾(低度扰动)或竞争优势排除了其他人。 年度火灾(高度扰动)或只有防火物种存活下来。 每3-5年的火灾(中度扰动)防止竞争性排斥,但对于火灾敏感物种在烧伤之间建立、最大限度地实现多样性而言,其频率并不高。",
  "Important Concepts": "重要概念",
  "A study of grassland communities found that fire frequency determines species diversity. Plots that never burned became dominated by a few tall grass species. Plots burned every year supported only fire-resistant species. But plots burned every 3-5 years had the highest species diversity — both fire-tolerant and fire-sensitive species coexisted. Which concept does this BEST support": "对草原社区的一项研究发现,火灾频度决定了物种多样性,从未被烧毁的地块以少数高高的草种为主,每年被烧毁的地块只支持耐火的物种,但每3-5年被烧毁的地块都有最高的物种多样性,既能防火,又能防火的敏感物种共存。"
}